entry.title: Blizzard Warning issued February 22 at 6:39AM AKST until February 22 at 9:00PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
...ACCUMULATING SNOW AND HIGH WINDS FOR THE KLONDIKE HIGHWAY...
.A quick moving front will impact the panhandle today, bringing accumulating snow to the Klondike Highway above 1500 feet. Blowing snow will lead to significant reductions in visibility. If temperatures are lower than expected, snowfall accumulations could be higher than currently anticipated.
* WHAT...Blizzard conditions expected. Total snow accumulations of up to 8 inches. Winds gusting as high as 60 mph. Visibilities reduced to 1/4 mile at times in blowing snow.
* WHERE...Klondike Highway.
* WHEN...From 9 AM to 9 PM AKST Thursday.
* IMPACTS...Travel will be very difficult. Areas of blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. Strong winds could cause tree damage.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snowfall totals will be largely dependent on how far warm air can move up from Skagway into the Klondike Highway. Snow that does fall will reduce visibilities substantially.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 22 at 5:20AM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
A series of systems moving into Southeast Alaska beginning on Thursday and continuing through the weekend will bring with them a return of widespread rain, wind, and snow. The first system will arrive on Thursday, bringing with it widespread rainfall, with between 1 - 2 inches of rain expected across much of the panhandle. Alongside the rain, windy conditions are expected, especially for the northern and central panhandle. Snow and high winds along the Klondike Highway will contribute to significantly reduced visibility at times through the day. Some areas may see a brief period of snow, with minor snow accumulations as the system departs Thursday night and cooler air enters the panhandle.
The second system, arrives the latter half of Friday and lasts through Saturday. This will drop temperatures into the weekend with rain transitioning to snow to areas ranging from Petersburg northward. Snow will start heavy and wet then become drier and lighter as the cold air moves in. The greatest snow totals anticipated in Juneau, Alaska.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Municipality of Skagway; City and Borough of Juneau

cap:parameter.value: SYSTEMS BRING SNOW, RAIN, AND WIND THROUGH THE WEEKEND

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 21 at 9:02PM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary: Another round of strong winds are building this evening and will reach peak intensity tonight as a low pressure system moves up Cook Inlet. Expect southeast winds gusting 40 to 60 mph through most of the Anchorage Municipality. A rain/snow mix is possible this evening, with more of a wet snow expected at higher elevations. Winds will likely last through midnight before diminishing early Thursday morning. Precipitation is most likely in the early morning hours and is expected to fall mostly as snow with the arrival of a cooler southwesterly flow. The timing of the changeover to snow will dictate accumulations, with 1 to 3 inches possible at sea level and 4 to 8 inches possible at higher elevations. The addition of snow and below-freezing temperatures to wet roadways may create difficult travel conditions.
